# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: horizontal-pod-autoscaling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] To do this, a **controller** with the requisite corrective behavior is required.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This controller monitors the controlled process variable (PV), and compares it with the reference or set point (SP).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The difference between actual and desired value of the process variable, called the *error* signal, or SP-PV error, is applied as feedback to generate a control action to bring the controlled process variable to the same value as the set point.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Other aspects which are also studied are controllability and observability.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control theory is used in control system engineering to design automation that have revolutionized manufacturing, aircraft, communications and other industries, and created new fields such as robotics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Extensive use is usually made of a diagrammatic style known as the block diagram.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In it the transfer function, also known as the system function or network function, is a mathematical model of the relation between the input and output based on the differential equations describing the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control theory dates from the 19th century, when the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control theory was further advanced by Edward Routh in 1874, Charles Sturm and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, who all contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria; and from 1922 onwards, the development of PID control theory by Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Although the most direct application of mathematical control theory is its use in control systems engineering (dealing with process control systems for robotics and industry), control theory is routinely applied to problems both the natural and behavioral sciences.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] As the general theory of feedback systems, control theory is useful wherever feedback occurs, making it important to fields like economics, operations research, and the life sciences.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Although control systems of various types date back to antiquity, a more formal analysis of the field began with a dynamics analysis of the centrifugal governor, conducted by the physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1868, entitled *On Governors*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A centrifugal governor was already used to regulate the velocity of windmills.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Maxwell described and analyzed the phenomenon of self-oscillation, in which lags in the system may lead to overcompensation and unstable behavior.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This generated a flurry of interest in the topic, during which Maxwell's classmate, Edward John Routh, abstracted Maxwell's results for the general class of linear systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Independently, Adolf Hurwitz analyzed system stability using differential equations in 1877, resulting in what is now known as the Routh–Hurwitz theorem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A notable application of dynamic control was in the area of crewed flight.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The Wright brothers made their first successful test flights on December 17, 1903, and were distinguished by their ability to control their flights for substantial periods (more so than the ability to produce lift from an airfoil, which was known).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Continuous, reliable control of the airplane was necessary for flights lasting longer than a few seconds.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] By World War II, control theory was becoming an important area of research.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control systems, and applied the bang-bang principle to the development of automatic flight control equipment for aircraft.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Other areas of application for discontinuous controls included fire-control systems, guidance systems and electronics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Sometimes, mechanical methods are used to improve the stability of systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] For example, ship stabilizers are fins mounted beneath the waterline and emerging laterally.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In contemporary vessels, they may be gyroscopically controlled active fins, which have the capacity to change their angle of attack to counteract roll caused by wind or waves acting on the ship.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The Space Race also depended on accurate spacecraft control, and control theory has also seen an increasing use in fields such as economics and artificial intelligence.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Here, one might say that the goal is to find an internal model that obeys the good regulator theorem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] So, for example, in economics, the more accurately a (stock or commodities) trading model represents the actions of the market, the more easily it can control that market (and extract "useful work" (profits) from it).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These last two examples take the narrow historical interpretation of control theory as a set of differential equations modeling and regulating kinetic motion, and broaden it into a vast generalization of a regulator interacting with a plant.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A closed-loop controller or feedback controller is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In contrast to the frequency-domain analysis of the classical control theory, modern control theory utilizes the time-domain state space representation, a mathematical model of a physical system as a set of input, output and state variables related by first-order differential equations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] To abstract from the number of inputs, outputs, and states, the variables are expressed as vectors and the differential and algebraic equations are written in matrix form (the latter only being possible when the dynamical system is linear).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The state space representation (also known as the "time-domain approach") provides a convenient and compact way to model and analyze systems with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] With inputs and outputs, we would otherwise have to write down Laplace transforms to encode all the information about a system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Unlike the frequency domain approach, the use of the state-space representation is not limited to systems with linear components and zero initial conditions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] "State space" refers to the space whose axes are the state variables.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The state of the system can be represented as a point within that space.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control systems can be divided into different categories depending on the number of inputs and outputs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The scope of classical control theory is limited to single-input and single-output (SISO) system design, except when analyzing for disturbance rejection using a second input.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The system analysis is carried out in the time domain using differential equations, in the complex-s domain with the Laplace transform, or in the frequency domain by transforming from the complex-s domain.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Many systems may be assumed to have a second order and single variable system response in the time domain.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A controller designed using classical theory often requires on-site tuning due to incorrect design approximations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Yet, due to the easier physical implementation of classical controller designs as compared to systems designed using modern control theory, these controllers are preferred in most industrial applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The most common controllers designed using classical control theory are PID controllers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A less common implementation may include either or both a Lead or Lag filter.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The ultimate end goal is to meet requirements typically provided in the time-domain called the step response, or at times in the frequency domain called the open-loop response.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The step response characteristics applied in a specification are typically percent overshoot, settling time, etc.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The open-loop response characteristics applied in a specification are typically Gain and Phase margin and bandwidth.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These characteristics may be evaluated through simulation including a dynamic model of the system under control coupled with the compensation model.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Modern control theory is carried out in the state space, and can deal with multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This overcomes the limitations of classical control theory in more sophisticated design problems, such as fighter aircraft control, with the limitation that no frequency domain analysis is possible.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In modern design, a system is represented to the greatest advantage as a set of decoupled first order differential equations defined using state variables.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Nonlinear, multivariable, adaptive and robust control theories come under this division.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Being fairly new, modern control theory has many areas yet to be explored.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Kálmán and Aleksandr Lyapunov are well known among the people who have shaped modern control theory.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The *stability* of a general dynamical system with no input can be described with Lyapunov stability criteria.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] For simplicity, the following descriptions focus on continuous-time and discrete-time **linear systems**.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Mathematically, this means that for a causal linear system to be stable all of the poles of its transfer function must have negative-real values, i.e. the real part of each pole must be less than zero.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The difference between the two cases is simply due to the traditional method of plotting continuous time versus discrete time transfer functions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The continuous Laplace transform is in Cartesian coordinates where the x axis is the real axis and the discrete Z-transform is in circular coordinates where the $\rho$ axis is the real axis.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] When the appropriate conditions above are satisfied a system is said to be asymptotically stable; the variables of an asymptotically stable control system always decrease from their initial value and do not show permanent oscillations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Permanent oscillations occur when a pole has a real part exactly equal to zero (in the continuous time case) or a modulus equal to one (in the discrete time case).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] If a simply stable system response neither decays nor grows over time, and has no oscillations, it is marginally stable; in this case the system transfer function has non-repeated poles at the complex plane origin (i.e. their real and complex component is zero in the continuous time case).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Oscillations are present when poles with real part equal to zero have an imaginary part not equal to zero.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] which has a pole in $z=0.5$ (zero imaginary part).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This system is BIBO (asymptotically) stable since the pole is *inside* the unit circle.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] which has a pole at $z=1.5$ and is not BIBO stable since the pole has a modulus strictly greater than one.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Numerous tools exist for the analysis of the poles of a system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These include graphical systems like the root locus, Bode plots or the Nyquist plots.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Mechanical changes can make equipment (and control systems) more stable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Sailors add ballast to improve the stability of ships.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Cruise ships use antiroll fins that extend transversely from the side of the ship for perhaps 30 feet (10 m) and are continuously rotated about their axes to develop forces that oppose the roll.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Controllability and observability are main issues in the analysis of a system before deciding the best control strategy to be applied, or whether it is even possible to control or stabilize the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Controllability is related to the possibility of forcing the system into a particular state by using an appropriate control signal.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, then no signal will ever be able to control the state.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, but its dynamics are stable, then the state is termed *stabilizable*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Observability instead is related to the possibility of *observing*, through output measurements, the state of a system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] If a state is not observable, the controller will never be able to determine the behavior of an unobservable state and hence cannot use it to stabilize the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] However, similar to the stabilizability condition above, if a state cannot be observed it might still be detectable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] From a geometrical point of view, looking at the states of each variable of the system to be controlled, every "bad" state of these variables must be controllable and observable to ensure a good behavior in the closed-loop system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] That is, if one of the eigenvalues of the system is not both controllable and observable, this part of the dynamics will remain untouched in the closed-loop system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] If such an eigenvalue is not stable, the dynamics of this eigenvalue will be present in the closed-loop system which therefore will be unstable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Unobservable poles are not present in the transfer function realization of a state-space representation, which is why sometimes the latter is preferred in dynamical systems analysis.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Solutions to problems of an uncontrollable or unobservable system include adding actuators and sensors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Several different control strategies have been devised in the past years.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These vary from extremely general ones (PID controller), to others devoted to very particular classes of systems (especially robotics or aircraft cruise control).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A control problem can have several specifications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Stability, of course, is always present.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The controller must ensure that the closed-loop system is stable, regardless of the open-loop stability.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A poor choice of controller can even worsen the stability of the open-loop system, which must normally be avoided.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Sometimes it would be desired to obtain particular dynamics in the closed loop: i.e. that the poles have $Re[\lambda ]<-{\overline {\lambda }}$ , where ${\overline {\lambda }}$ is a fixed value strictly greater than zero, instead of simply asking that $Re[\lambda ]<0$ .
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Another typical specification is the rejection of a step disturbance; including an integrator in the open-loop chain (i.e. directly before the system under control) easily achieves this.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Other classes of disturbances need different types of sub-systems to be included.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Other "classical" control theory specifications regard the time-response of the closed-loop system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These include the rise time (the time needed by the control system to reach the desired value after a perturbation), peak overshoot (the highest value reached by the response before reaching the desired value) and others (settling time, quarter-decay).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Frequency domain specifications are usually related to robustness (see after).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Modern performance assessments use some variation of integrated tracking error (IAE, ISA, CQI).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A control system must always have some robustness property.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A robust controller is such that its properties do not change much if applied to a system slightly different from the mathematical one used for its synthesis.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This requirement is important, as no real physical system truly behaves like the series of differential equations used to represent it mathematically.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Typically a simpler mathematical model is chosen in order to simplify calculations, otherwise, the true system dynamics can be so complicated that a complete model is impossible.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The process of determining the equations that govern the model's dynamics is called system identification.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This can be done off-line: for example, executing a series of measures from which to calculate an approximated mathematical model, typically its transfer function or matrix.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Such identification from the output, however, cannot take account of unobservable dynamics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Sometimes the model is built directly starting from known physical equations, for example, in the case of a mass-spring-damper system we know that $m{\ddot {x}}(t)=-Kx(t)-\mathrm {B} {\dot {x}}(t)$ .
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Some advanced control techniques include an "on-line" identification process (see later).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The parameters of the model are calculated ("identified") while the controller itself is running.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In this way, if a drastic variation of the parameters ensues, for example, if the robot's arm releases a weight, the controller will adjust itself consequently in order to ensure the correct performance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Analysis of the robustness of a SISO (single input single output) control system can be performed in the frequency domain, considering the system's transfer function and using Nyquist and Bode diagrams.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Topics include gain and phase margin and amplitude margin.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] For MIMO (multi-input multi output) and, in general, more complicated control systems, one must consider the theoretical results devised for each control technique (see next section).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] I.e., if particular robustness qualities are needed, the engineer must shift their attention to a control technique by including these qualities in its properties.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A particular robustness issue is the requirement for a control system to perform properly in the presence of input and state constraints.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In the physical world every signal is limited.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] It could happen that a controller will send control signals that cannot be followed by the physical system, for example, trying to rotate a valve at excessive speed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] This can produce undesired behavior of the closed-loop system, or even damage or break actuators or other subsystems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Specific control techniques are available to solve the problem: model predictive control (see later), and anti-wind up systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The latter consists of an additional control block that ensures that the control signal never exceeds a given threshold.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] For MIMO systems, pole placement can be performed mathematically using a state space representation of the open-loop system and calculating a feedback matrix assigning poles in the desired positions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In complicated systems this can require computer-assisted calculation capabilities, and cannot always ensure robustness.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Furthermore, all system states are not in general measured and so observers must be included and incorporated in pole placement design.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Processes in industries like robotics and the aerospace industry typically have strong nonlinear dynamics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] In control theory it is sometimes possible to linearize such classes of systems and apply linear techniques, but in many cases it can be necessary to devise from scratch theories permitting control of nonlinear systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] These, e.g., feedback linearization, backstepping, sliding mode control, trajectory linearization control normally take advantage of results based on Lyapunov's theory.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Differential geometry has been widely used as a tool for generalizing well-known linear control concepts to the nonlinear case, as well as showing the subtleties that make it a more challenging problem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Control theory has also been used to decipher the neural mechanism that directs cognitive states.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] When the system is controlled by multiple controllers, the problem is one of decentralized control.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Decentralization is helpful in many ways, for instance, it helps control systems to operate over a larger geographical area.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The agents in decentralized control systems can interact using communication channels and coordinate their actions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A stochastic control problem is one in which the evolution of the state variables is subjected to random shocks from outside the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] A deterministic control problem is not subject to external random shocks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Every control system must guarantee first the stability of the closed-loop behavior.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] For linear systems, this can be obtained by directly placing the poles.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] Nonlinear control systems use specific theories (normally based on Aleksandr Lyapunov's Theory) to ensure stability without regard to the inner dynamics of the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/control-theory] The possibility to fulfill different specifications varies from the model considered and the control strategy chosen.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] In computing, **elasticity** is defined as "the degree to which a system is able to adapt to workload changes by provisioning and de-provisioning resources in an autonomic manner, such that at each point in time the available resources match the current demand as closely as possible".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity is a defining characteristic that differentiates cloud computing from previously proposed distributed computing paradigms, such as grid computing.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The dynamic adaptation of capacity, e.g., by altering the use of computing resources, to meet a varying workload is called "elastic computing".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] In the world of distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors; some consider the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity aims to match the amount of resources allocated to a service with the amount of resources it actually requires, avoiding over- or under-provisioning.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] **Over-provisioning**, i.e., allocating more resources than required, should be avoided as it may incur extra costs (monetary, energy, operational, etc.) for unused or underutilized resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, if a website is over-provisioned with two cloud computing resources to handle current demand that only requires one resource, the costs of maintaining the second resource would effectively be wasted.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity can be illustrated through an example of a service provider who wants to run a website on the cloud.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{0}$ , the website is unpopular and a single machine is sufficient to serve all users.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{1}$ , the website suddenly becomes popular, and a single machine is no longer sufficient to serve all users.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Based on the number of web users simultaneously accessing the website and the resource requirements of the web server, ten machines are needed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and provision nine additional machines from the cloud to serve all users responsively.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] At time $t_{2}$ , the website becomes unpopular again.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The ten machines currently allocated to the website are mostly idle and a single machine would be sufficient to serve the few users who are accessing the website.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and deprovision nine machines, releasing them to the cloud.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user; however, it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] The VM startup time is dependent on factors such as image size, VM type, data center location, number of VMs, etc.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] This implies that any control mechanism designed for elastic applications must consider the time needed for the resource provisioning actions to take effect.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic applications can allocate and deallocate resources on demand for specific application components.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] This makes cloud resources volatile, and traditional monitoring tools which associate monitoring data with a particular resource, such as Ganglia or Nagios, are no longer suitable for monitoring the *behavior* of elastic applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, during its lifetime, a data storage tier of an elastic application might add and remove data storage VMs due to cost and performance requirements, varying the number of used VMs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Thus, additional information is needed in monitoring elastic applications, such as associating the logical application structure over the underlying virtual infrastructure.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] When deploying applications in cloud infrastructures (IaaS/PaaS), stakeholder requirements need to be considered in order to ensure that elastic behavior meets stakeholder needs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Traditionally, the optimal trade-off between cost and quality or performance is considered; however, for real world cloud users, requirements regarding elastic behavior are more complex and target multiple dimensions of elasticity (e.g., SYBL).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud applications vary in type and complexity, with multiple levels of artifacts deployed in layers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Controlling such structures must take into consideration a variety of issues.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic strategies on in cloud computing can take advantage of control-theoretic methods (e.g., predictive control has been experimented in cloud computing scenarios by showing considerable advantages with respect to reactive methods).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/elasticity-cloud-computing] One approach to multi-level elastic clouc control is rSYBL.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In Kubernetes, a *HorizontalPodAutoscaler* automatically updates a workload resource (such as a Deployment or StatefulSet), with the aim of automatically scaling capacity to match demand.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Horizontal scaling means that the response to increased load is to deploy more Pods.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This is different from *vertical* scaling, which for Kubernetes would mean assigning more resources (for example: memory or CPU) to the Pods that are already running for the workload.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If the load decreases, and the number of Pods is above the configured minimum, the HorizontalPodAutoscaler instructs the workload resource (the Deployment, StatefulSet, or other similar resource) to scale back down.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler is implemented as a Kubernetes API resource and a controller.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The resource determines the behavior of the controller.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The horizontal pod autoscaling controller, running within the Kubernetes control plane, periodically adjusts the desired scale of its target (for example, a Deployment) to match observed metrics such as average CPU utilization, average memory utilization, or any other custom metric you specify.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] There is walkthrough example of using horizontal pod autoscaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Kubernetes implements horizontal pod autoscaling as a control loop that runs intermittently (it is not a continuous process).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The interval is set by the `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-sync-period` parameter to the `kube-controller-manager` (and the default interval is 15 seconds).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Once during each period, the controller manager queries the resource utilization against the metrics specified in each HorizontalPodAutoscaler definition.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The common use for HorizontalPodAutoscaler is to configure it to fetch metrics from aggregated APIs (`metrics.k8s.io`, `custom.metrics.k8s.io`, or `external.metrics.k8s.io`).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The `metrics.k8s.io` API is usually provided by an add-on named Metrics Server, which needs to be launched separately.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For more information about resource metrics, see Metrics Server.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Support for metrics APIs explains the stability guarantees and support status for these different APIs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler controller accesses corresponding workload resources that support scaling (such as Deployments and StatefulSet).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] These resources each have a subresource named `scale`, an interface that allows you to dynamically set the number of replicas and examine each of their current states.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For general information about subresources in the Kubernetes API, see Kubernetes API Concepts.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For example, if the current metric value is `200m`, and the desired value is `100m`, the number of replicas will be doubled, since \( { 200.0 \div 100.0 } = 2.0 \).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If the current value is instead `50m`, you'll halve the number of replicas, since \( { 50.0 \div 100.0 } = 0.5 \).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The control plane skips any scaling action if the ratio is sufficiently close to 1.0 (within a configurable tolerance, 0.1 by default).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When a `targetAverageValue` or `targetAverageUtilization` is specified, the `currentMetricValue` is computed by taking the average of the given metric across all Pods in the HorizontalPodAutoscaler's scale target.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Before checking the tolerance and deciding on the final values, the control plane also considers whether any metrics are missing, and how many Pods are `Ready`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For per-pod resource metrics, all Pods with a deletion timestamp set (objects with a deletion timestamp are in the process of being shut down / removed) are ignored, and all failed Pods are discarded.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For external and object metrics, the replica count is based on the number of Running and Ready Pods; terminating Pods that are still Ready continue to count toward that total.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If a particular Pod is missing metrics, it is set aside for later; Pods with missing metrics will be used to adjust the final scaling amount.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When scaling on CPU, if any pod has yet to become ready (it's still initializing, or possibly is unhealthy) *or* the most recent metric point for the pod was before it became ready, that pod is set aside as well.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Due to technical constraints, the HorizontalPodAutoscaler controller cannot exactly determine the first time a pod becomes ready when determining whether to set aside certain CPU metrics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Instead, it considers a Pod "not yet ready" if it's unready and transitioned to ready within a short, configurable window of time since it started.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This value is configured with the `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-initial-readiness-delay` command line option, and its default is 30 seconds.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Once a pod has become ready, it considers any transition to ready to be the first if it occurred within a longer, configurable time since it started.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This value is configured with the `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-cpu-initialization-period` command line option, and its default is 5 minutes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The \( currentMetricValue \over desiredMetricValue \) base scale ratio is then calculated, using the remaining pods not set aside or discarded from above.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If there were any missing metrics, the control plane recomputes the average more conservatively, assuming those pods were consuming 100% of the desired value in case of a scale down, and 0% in case of a scale up.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This dampens the magnitude of any potential scale.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] After factoring in the not-yet-ready pods and missing metrics, the controller recalculates the usage ratio.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If the new ratio reverses the scale direction, or is within the tolerance, the controller doesn't take any scaling action.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In other cases, the new ratio is used to decide any change to the number of Pods.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Note that the *original* value for the average utilization is reported back via the HorizontalPodAutoscaler status, without factoring in the not-yet-ready pods or missing metrics, even when the new usage ratio is used.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If multiple metrics are specified in a HorizontalPodAutoscaler, this calculation is done for each metric, and then the largest of the desired replica counts is chosen.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If any of these metrics cannot be converted into a desired replica count (e.g. due to an error fetching the metrics from the metrics APIs) and a scale down is suggested by the metrics which can be fetched, scaling is skipped.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This means that the HPA is still capable of scaling up if one or more metrics give a `desiredReplicas` greater than the current value.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Finally, right before HPA scales the target, the scale recommendation is recorded.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The controller considers all recommendations within a configurable window choosing the highest recommendation from within that window.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can configure this value using the `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-downscale-stabilization` command line option, which defaults to 5 minutes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This means that scaledowns will occur gradually, smoothing out the impact of rapidly fluctuating metric values.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This defines the time window after a Pod starts during which its **CPU usage is ignored** unless: - The Pod is in a `Ready` state **and** - The metric sample was taken entirely during the period it was `Ready`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This command line option helps **exclude misleading high CPU usage** from initializing Pods (for example: Java apps warming up) in HPA scaling decisions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This defines a short delay period after a Pod starts during which the HPA controller treats Pods that are currently `Unready` as still initializing, **even if they have previously transitioned to `Ready` briefly**.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] It is designed to: - Avoid including Pods that rapidly fluctuate between `Ready` and `Unready` during startup. - Ensure stability in the initial readiness signal before HPA considers their metrics valid.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can only set these command line options cluster-wide.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] And ideally also set `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-cpu-initialization-period` to **cover the startup duration**.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler is an API kind in the Kubernetes `autoscaling` API group.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The current stable version can be found in the `autoscaling/v2` API version which includes support for scaling on memory and custom metrics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The new fields introduced in `autoscaling/v2` are preserved as annotations when working with `autoscaling/v1`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When you create a HorizontalPodAutoscaler API object, make sure the name specified is a valid DNS subdomain name.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] More details about the API object can be found at HorizontalPodAutoscaler Object.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When managing the scale of a group of replicas using the HorizontalPodAutoscaler, it is possible that the number of replicas keeps fluctuating frequently due to the dynamic nature of the metrics evaluated.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This is sometimes referred to as *thrashing*, or *flapping*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] It's similar to the concept of *hysteresis* in cybernetics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Kubernetes lets you perform a rolling update on a Deployment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In that case, the Deployment manages the underlying ReplicaSets for you.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When you configure autoscaling for a Deployment, you bind a HorizontalPodAutoscaler to a single Deployment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler manages the `replicas` field of the Deployment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The deployment controller is responsible for setting the `replicas` of the underlying ReplicaSets so that they add up to a suitable number during the rollout and also afterwards.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you perform a rolling update of a StatefulSet that has an autoscaled number of replicas, the StatefulSet directly manages its set of Pods (there is no intermediate resource similar to ReplicaSet).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Any HPA target can be scaled based on the resource usage of the pods in the scaling target.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When defining the pod specification the resource requests like `cpu` and `memory` should be specified.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This is used to determine the resource utilization and used by the HPA controller to scale the target up or down.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] With this metric the HPA controller will keep the average utilization of the pods in the scaling target at 60%.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Utilization is the ratio between the current usage of resource to the requested resources of the pod.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] See Algorithm for more details about how the utilization is calculated and averaged.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Since the resource usages of all the containers are summed up the total pod utilization may not accurately represent the individual container resource usage.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This could lead to situations where a single container might be running with high usage and the HPA will not scale out because the overall pod usage is still within acceptable limits.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler API also supports a container metric source where the HPA can track the resource usage of individual containers across a set of Pods, in order to scale the target resource.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This lets you configure scaling thresholds for the containers that matter most in a particular Pod.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For example, if you have a web application and a sidecar container that provides logging, you can scale based on the resource use of the web application, ignoring the sidecar container and its resource use.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you revise the target resource to have a new Pod specification with a different set of containers, you should revise the HPA spec if that newly added container should also be used for scaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If the specified container in the metric source is not present or only present in a subset of the pods then those pods are ignored and the recommendation is recalculated.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] See Algorithm for more details about the calculation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In the above example the HPA controller scales the target such that the average utilization of the cpu in the `application` container of all the pods is 60%.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you change the name of a container that a HorizontalPodAutoscaler is tracking, you can make that change in a specific order to ensure scaling remains available and effective whilst the change is being applied.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Before you update the resource that defines the container (such as a Deployment), you should update the associated HPA to track both the new and old container names.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This way, the HPA is able to calculate a scaling recommendation throughout the update process.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Once you have rolled out the container name change to the workload resource, tidy up by removing the old container name from the HPA specification.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Provided that you use the `autoscaling/v2` API version, you can configure a HorizontalPodAutoscaler to scale based on a custom metric (that is not built in to Kubernetes or any Kubernetes component).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler controller then queries for these custom metrics from the Kubernetes API.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] See Support for metrics APIs for the requirements.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Provided that you use the `autoscaling/v2` API version, you can specify multiple metrics for a HorizontalPodAutoscaler to scale on.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Then, the HorizontalPodAutoscaler controller evaluates each metric, and proposes a new scale based on that metric.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The HorizontalPodAutoscaler takes the maximum scale recommended for each metric and sets the workload to that size (provided that this isn't larger than the overall maximum that you configured).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] By default, the HorizontalPodAutoscaler controller retrieves metrics from a series of APIs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For more information on these different metrics paths and how they differ please see the relevant design proposals for the HPA V2, custom.metrics.k8s.io and external.metrics.k8s.io.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For examples of how to use them see the walkthrough for using custom metrics and the walkthrough for using external metrics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you use the `v2` HorizontalPodAutoscaler API, you can use the `behavior` field (see the API reference) to configure separate scale-up and scale-down behaviors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You specify these behaviors by setting `scaleUp` and / or `scaleDown` under the `behavior` field.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Scaling policies let you control the rate of change of replicas while scaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Also two settings can be used to prevent flapping: you can specify a *stabilization window* for smoothing replica counts, and a tolerance to ignore minor metric fluctuations below a specified threshold.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] One or more scaling policies can be specified in the `behavior` section of the spec.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When multiple policies are specified the policy which allows the highest amount of change is the policy which is selected by default.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] `periodSeconds` indicates the length of time in the past for which the policy must hold true.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The maximum value that you can set for `periodSeconds` is 1800 (half an hour).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The first policy *(Pods)* allows at most 4 replicas to be scaled down in one minute.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The second policy *(Percent)* allows at most 10% of the current replicas to be scaled down in one minute.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Since by default the policy which allows the highest amount of change is selected, the second policy will only be used when the number of pod replicas is more than 40.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] With 40 or less replicas, the first policy will be applied.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For instance if there are 80 replicas and the target has to be scaled down to 10 replicas then during the first step 8 replicas will be reduced.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In the next iteration when the number of replicas is 72, 10% of the pods is 7.2 but the number is rounded up to 8.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] On each loop of the autoscaler controller the number of pods to be change is re-calculated based on the number of current replicas.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When the number of replicas falls below 40 the first policy *(Pods)* is applied and 4 replicas will be reduced at a time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The policy selection can be changed by specifying the `selectPolicy` field for a scaling direction.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] By setting the value to `Min` which would select the policy which allows the smallest change in the replica count.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Setting the value to `Disabled` completely disables scaling in that direction.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The stabilization window is used to restrict the flapping of replica count when the metrics used for scaling keep fluctuating.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The autoscaling algorithm uses this window to infer a previous desired state and avoid unwanted changes to workload scale.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For example, in the following example snippet, a stabilization window is specified for `scaleDown`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When the metrics indicate that the target should be scaled down the algorithm looks into previously computed desired states, and uses the highest value from the specified interval.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In the above example, all desired states from the past 5 minutes will be considered.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This approximates a rolling maximum, and avoids having the scaling algorithm frequently remove Pods only to trigger recreating an equivalent Pod just moments later.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The `tolerance` field configures a threshold for metric variations, preventing the autoscaler from scaling for changes below that value.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This tolerance is defined as the amount of variation around the desired metric value under which no scaling will occur.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] With this configuration, the HPA algorithm will only consider scaling up if the memory consumption is higher than 105MiB (that is: 5% above the target).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you don't set this field, the HPA applies the default cluster-wide tolerance of 10%.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This default can be updated for both scale-up and scale-down using the kube-controller-manager `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-tolerance` command line argument.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] To use the custom scaling not all fields have to be specified.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Only values which need to be customized can be specified.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] These custom values are merged with default values.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The default values match the existing behavior in the HPA algorithm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For scaling down the stabilization window is *300* seconds (or the value of the `--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-downscale-stabilization` command line option, if provided).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] There is only a single policy for scaling down which allows a 100% of the currently running replicas to be removed which means the scaling target can be scaled down to the minimum allowed replicas.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For scaling up there is no stabilization window.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When the metrics indicate that the target should be scaled up the target is scaled up immediately.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] There are 2 policies where 4 pods or a 100% of the currently running replicas may at most be added every 15 seconds till the HPA reaches its steady state.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] To ensure that no more than 5 Pods are removed per minute, you can add a second scale-down policy with a fixed size of 5, and set `selectPolicy` to minimum.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] The `selectPolicy` value of `Disabled` turns off scaling the given direction.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] HorizontalPodAutoscaler, like every API resource, is supported in a standard way by `kubectl`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can create a new autoscaler using `kubectl create` command.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can list autoscalers by `kubectl get hpa` or get detailed description by `kubectl describe hpa`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Finally, you can delete an autoscaler using `kubectl delete hpa`.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] In addition, there is a special `kubectl autoscale` command for creating a HorizontalPodAutoscaler object.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] For instance, executing `kubectl autoscale rs foo --min=2 --max=5 --cpu=80%` will create an autoscaler for ReplicaSet *foo*, with target CPU utilization set to `80%` and the number of replicas between 2 and 5.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can implicitly deactivate the HPA for a target without the need to change the HPA configuration itself.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When an HPA is enabled, it is recommended that the value of `spec.replicas` of the Deployment and / or StatefulSet be removed from their manifest(s).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If this isn't done, any time a change to that object is applied, for example via `kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml`, this will instruct Kubernetes to scale the current number of Pods to the value of the `spec.replicas` key.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] This may not be desired and could be troublesome when an HPA is active, resulting in thrashing or flapping behavior.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Keep in mind that the removal of `spec.replicas` may incur a one-time degradation of Pod counts as the default value of this key is 1 (reference Deployment Replicas).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Upon the update, all Pods except 1 will begin their termination procedures.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] Any deployment application afterwards will behave as normal and respect a rolling update configuration as desired.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When you save and exit the editor, `kubectl` applies the update.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] No changes to Pod counts happen at this step.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can now remove `spec.replicas` from the manifest.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you use source code management, also commit your changes or take whatever other steps for revising the source code are appropriate for how you track updates.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] When using the Server-Side Apply you can follow the transferring ownership guidelines, which cover this exact use case.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] If you configure autoscaling in your cluster, you may also want to consider using node autoscaling to ensure you are running the right number of nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/horizontal-pod-autoscale] You can also read more about *vertical* Pod autoscaling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
