[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In an economic context, a scalable business model implies that a company can increase sales given increased resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example, a package delivery system is scalable because more packages can be delivered by adding more delivery vehicles.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] However, if all packages had to first pass through a single warehouse for sorting, the system would not be as scalable, because one warehouse can handle only a limited number of packages.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In computing, scalability is a characteristic of computers, networks, algorithms, networking protocols, programs and applications.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] An example is a search engine, which must support increasing numbers of users, and the number of topics it indexes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] **Webscale** is a computer architectural approach that brings the capabilities of large-scale cloud computing companies into enterprise data centers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors, some considering the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but you need to consider total cost of ownership not just the infra cost.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In mathematics, scalability mostly refers to closure under scalar multiplication.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In industrial engineering and manufacturing, scalability refers to the capacity of a process, system, or organization to handle a growing workload, adapt to increasing demands, and maintain operational efficiency.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] A scalable system can effectively manage increased production volumes, new product lines, or expanding markets without compromising quality or performance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In this context, scalability is a vital consideration for businesses aiming to meet customer expectations, remain competitive, and achieve sustainable growth.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Factors influencing scalability include the flexibility of the production process, the adaptability of the workforce, and the integration of advanced technologies.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] By implementing scalable solutions, companies can optimize resource utilization, reduce costs, and streamline their operations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scalability in industrial engineering and manufacturing enables businesses to respond to fluctuating market conditions, capitalize on emerging opportunities, and thrive in an ever-evolving global landscape.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The Incident Command System (ICS) is used by emergency response agencies in the United States.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] ICS can scale resource coordination from a single-engine roadside brushfire to an interstate wildfire.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The first resource on scene establishes command, with authority to order resources and delegate responsibility (managing five to seven officers, who will again delegate to up to seven, and on as the incident grows).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] As an incident expands, more senior officers assume command.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Resources fall into two broad categories: horizontal and vertical.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scaling horizontally (out/in) means adding or removing nodes, such as adding a new computer to a distributed software application.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] An example might involve scaling out from one web server to three.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] High-performance computing applications, such as seismic analysis and biotechnology, scale workloads horizontally to support tasks that once would have required expensive supercomputers.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Other workloads, such as large social networks, exceed the capacity of the largest supercomputer and can only be handled by scalable systems.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Exploiting this scalability requires software for efficient resource management and maintenance.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scaling vertically (up/down) means adding resources to (or removing resources from) a single node, typically involving the addition of CPUs, memory or storage to a single computer.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Benefits to scale-up include avoiding increased management complexity, more sophisticated programming to allocate tasks among resources and handling issues such as throughput, latency, and synchronization across nodes.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Moreover some applications do not scale horizontally.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Network function virtualization defines these terms differently: scaling out/in is the ability to scale by adding/removing resource instances (e.g., virtual machine), whereas scaling up/down is the ability to scale by changing allocated resources (e.g., memory/CPU/storage capacity).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scalability for databases requires that the database system be able to perform additional work given greater hardware resources, such as additional servers, processors, memory and storage.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Workloads have continued to grow and demands on databases have followed suit.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Algorithmic innovations include row-level locking and table and index partitioning.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Architectural innovations include shared-nothing and shared-everything architectures for managing multi-server configurations.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In the context of scale-out data storage, scalability is defined as the maximum storage cluster size which guarantees full data consistency, meaning there is only ever one valid version of stored data in the whole cluster, independently from the number of redundant physical data copies.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Clusters which provide "lazy" redundancy by updating copies in an asynchronous fashion are called 'eventually consistent'.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] This type of scale-out design is suitable when availability and responsiveness are rated higher than consistency, which is true for many web file-hosting services or web caches (*if you want the latest version, wait some seconds for it to propagate*).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For all classical transaction-oriented applications, this design should be avoided.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Many open-source and even commercial scale-out storage clusters, especially those built on top of standard PC hardware and networks, provide eventual consistency only, such as some NoSQL databases like CouchDB and others mentioned above.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Write operations invalidate other copies, but often don't wait for their acknowledgements.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Read operations typically don't check every redundant copy prior to answering, potentially missing the preceding write operation.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The large amount of metadata signal traffic would require specialized hardware and short distances to be handled with acceptable performance (i.e., act like a non-clustered storage device or database).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] It is often advised to focus system design on hardware scalability rather than on capacity.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] It is typically cheaper to add a new node to a system in order to achieve improved performance than to partake in performance tuning to improve the capacity that each node can handle.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] But this approach can have diminishing returns (as discussed in performance engineering).
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example: suppose 70% of a program can be sped up if parallelized and run on multiple CPUs instead of one.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Doubling the processing power has only sped up the process by roughly one-fifth.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] If the whole problem was parallelizable, the speed would also double.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Therefore, throwing in more hardware is not necessarily the optimal approach.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In distributed systems, you can use Universal Scalability Law (USL) to model and to optimize scalability of your system.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Gunther and quantifies scalability based on parameters such as contention and coherency.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Contention refers to delay due to waiting or queueing for shared resources.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Coherence refers to delay for data to become consistent.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example, having a high contention indicates sequential processing that could be parallelized, while having a high coherency suggests excessive dependencies among processes, prompting you to minimize interactions.
[src:horizontal-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Also, with help of USL, you can, in advance, calculate the maximum effective capacity of your system: scaling up your system beyond that point is a waste.
